Understanding NumPy's ndarray¶

NumPy's most amazing feature is the powerful ndarray.

1-Dimensional Arrays (Vectors)¶

In [3]:
array_1d = np.array([1,2,3,4,5])
array_1d
Out[3]:
array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
In [8]:
array_1d[2]
Out[8]:
3
In [7]:
print(array_1d.shape)
print(array_1d.ndim)

(5,)
1

2-Dimensional Arrays (Matrices)¶

In [18]:
array_2d = np.array([[1, 2, 3, 9], 
                     [5, 6, 7, 8]])
In [19]:
print(f"The array array_2d contains {array_2d.ndim} dimensions.")
print(f"The shape of array_2d has {array_2d.shape[0]} rows and has {array_2d.shape[1]} columns.")
print(array_2d)

The array array_2d contains 2 dimensions.
The shape of array_2d has 2 rows and has 4 columns.
[[1 2 3 9]
 [5 6 7 8]]

                           [4, 5, 6, 7]],
                        
                         [[7, 86, 6, 98],
                          [5, 1, 0, 4]],
                          
                          [[5, 36, 32, 48],

print(f"The tensor mystery_array has {mystery_array.shape[0]} rows and has {mystery_array.shape[1]} columns.")

The dimension of mystery_array is of 3.
The tensor mystery_array has 3 rows and has 2 columns.

Matrix Multiplication with @ and .matmul()¶

In [81]:
a1 = np.array([[1, 3],
               [0, 1],
               [6, 2],
               [9, 7]])

b1 = np.array([[4, 1, 3],
               [5, 8, 5]])

print(f'{a1.shape}: a has {a1.shape[0]} rows and {a1.shape[1]} columns.')
print(f'{b1.shape}: b has {b1.shape[0]} rows and {b1.shape[1]} columns.')
print('Dimensions of result: (4x2)*(2x3)=(4x3)')

(4, 2): a has 4 rows and 2 columns.
(2, 3): b has 2 rows and 3 columns.
Dimensions of result: (4x2)*(2x3)=(4x3)

Challenge: Let's multiply a1 with b1. Looking at the wikipedia example above, work out the values for c12 and c33 on paper. Then use the .matmul() function or the @ operator to check your work.

Challenge: Can you manipulate the images by doing some operations on the underlying ndarrays? See if you can change the values in the ndarray so that:

  1. You flip the image upside down

  2. Rotate the colour image

  3. Invert (i.e., solarize) the colour image. To do this you need to converting all the pixels to their "opposite" value, so black (0) becomes white (255).

Challenge Solutions¶

In [124]:
flipped = np.flip(img)
plt.imshow(flipped)
Out[124]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x18357770290>
In [106]:
rotate = np.rot90(img)
plt.imshow(rotate)
Out[106]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x1835166cbf0>
In [107]:
solarize = plt.imshow(255-img)
